The Rursus was probably first acted in the year ac. 19² ¹. The scene is laid on the coast in the neighbourhood of Cyrene.

The plot¹ is based upon the recovery by a fisherman, called Gripus, oi a vidulus, or wicker bashet used as a paching case, which has been lost at sea and which contains among other articles the crepundia or ‘tohens’ ol the heroine Palaestra, who has fallen into the hands oia slave-dealer, Labrax. Labrax is attempting to carry her off by sea to Sicily; but the ship is wreclred upon the African coast, in the neigh- bourhood ol Cyrene. Those on board escape dronning, but their property goes to the bottom. The play derives its name ‘The Rope,' from an amusing scene (IV. 3) in which Gripus, carrying the vr'dulus which he has¹ fished up, and trailing behind him a rope which is attached to it, is accosted by Trachalio—the slave ol Plesidippus ⁸, an Athenian youth and the lover ol Palaestra. Trachalio, who is acting in the interest oi the heroine, seizes the other end of the rope and demands that Gripus shall restore the booty to its rightsul owner.
